turns: Hillary Clinton's security detail added a second Scooby van to her motorcade during a visit to a fruit processing company in Iowa. The two identical vans are mechanically identical, with raised roofs, deep-tinted windows, and New York license plates. The Secret Service often uses decoy vehicles to confuse and discourage potential attackers. The two Scooby vans and four black Suburbans, as well as other vehicles, made up Clinton's seven-car motorcade. The Secret Service employs similar tactics for other VIPs, including using decoy aircraft and cars for Marine One, the president's helicopter.

A Georgia mother of six, Kalimah Dixon, is facing homelessness after a fire destroyed her rented condo, leaving her family with nothing. She is seeking assistance as she struggles to find a new home and provide stability for her children, who are due to take a standardized test on Tuesday. Dixon has started a GoFundMe page that has raised $4,619 in donations so far, and she is grateful for any help, including prayers.

An Australian couple abandoned a boy born through a surrogacy deal in India, leaving him stateless, according to new evidence. The couple, from New South Wales, where international surrogacy arrangements are illegal, reportedly told consular staff they wanted a baby girl to "complete their family." They planned to leave the boy behind because they couldn't afford to take care of him, and told staff they would give him to friends in India who couldn't conceive. Indian authorities were concerned that the boy may have been sold, as it is illegal to buy or sell children in the country. The case raises concerns about international surrogacy and the commodification of children.

Kecil, a baby orangutan, faced rejection from both his natural mother and a surrogate mother, but found love and care with Maggie, an experienced orangutan surrogate mother at the Brookfield Zoo in Chicago. Maggie has been raising Kecil for the past 10 months, and they share an inseparable bond. Initially, zookeepers were anxious that Maggie might reject Kecil, but she has proved her parenting skills once again. Kecil was moved to various zoos after being rejected by his first two surrogate mothers. After being introduced to Maggie, they immediately showed signs of intimacy, but keepers had to wait to see if Maggie would take on full parental duties. A fire alarm at the zoo frightened Kecil, and he ran to Maggie for comfort, which was a turning point in their relationship. Kecil will be on public display for the first time this weekend, alongside Maggie, in two-hour slots between 10 a.m. and midday, allowing him to nap in the afternoons. The pair will eventually join the zoo's other four orangutans in an enclosure but are currently living in isolation, as they would in the wild. Keepers are excited to see Kecil's development and his relationship with Maggie grow stronger.

Paris Saint-Germain star Javier Pastore has dismissed Eric Cantona's claim that he is the greatest footballer on the planet. Cantona, the former Manchester United forward, had praised Pastore as 'the best player in the world,' but Pastore believes Lionel Messi and Cristiano Ronaldo are a class above him. Before Tuesday's crucial Champions League match against Barcelona, Pastore expressed gratitude for Cantona's compliments but maintained that Messi and Ronaldo are exceptional players. Pastore scored a brace in PSG's 3-1 win at Nice on Saturday, helping the team reclaim top spot in Ligue 1.

Amanda Burleigh, a midwife, won a decade-long battle to give mothers more time attached to their newborns before the umbilical cord is cut. Traditionally, doctors and midwives have clamped the cord within seconds of delivery, but Burleigh believed it was unnatural and harmful. She and other medics amassed evidence that immediate cord-clamping could be harmful, particularly for premature babies, raising the risk of iron deficiency anemia and other issues. They succeeded in getting the National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE) to change its guidelines, recommending a one-minute wait before clamping for all babies and leaving the cord longer if the mother requests. The change has medical benefits and allows for a more meaningful bonding experience between mother and child. However, some doctors still resist the change, despite growing evidence against immediate cord-clamping.

French President Francois Hollande has vowed to "show no mercy" if French peacekeepers are found guilty of sexually assaulting starving children in the Central African Republic. Fourteen soldiers are accused of abusing children as young as nine in exchange for food between December 2013 and June 2014. The French defense ministry denies covering up the scandal and says it immediately launched an investigation when it received a leaked UN report on the subject in July 2015. A UN spokesman confirmed that investigators conducted a probe last year following "serious allegations" of child abuse and sexual exploitation by French troops.

A shocking "resurrection ceremony" for a two-year-old dead boy was caught on camera at a Texas church. The boy, identified by a witness as Benjamin, was allegedly possessed by demons, according to pastors. The ceremony was led by Aracely Meza, reportedly not the child's mother, who has been arrested and charged with injury to a child by omission. Police went to the home for a welfare check and found out about the "rising ceremony" after the child's death. The ceremony took place at a residence that also operated as Iglesia Internacional Jesus es el Rey Church, presided by Daniel and Aracely Meza. Neighbors reported that cars would fill the street for services but were unaware of what occurred inside the home. The home was not registered or zoned to operate as a church. Investigations are underway involving both state and federal authorities.

John Higgins and Graeme Dott, two Scottish thoroughbreds, had a successful start at the Betfred World Championship. Higgins beat Robert Milkins 10-5, showcasing impressive form, while Dott defeated Ricky Walden 10-8. Higgins, a four-time champion, credited his recent Welsh Open victory for the boost in his performance. He hopes to equal Ronnie O'Sullivan's total of five world titles but recognizes the strong competition. Dott, the 2006 champion, also felt relief at his win and acknowledged the tough challenge posed by Walden. Both players are excited about the prospect of winning the championship and believe they have a chance, despite the presence of strong competitors.

Barcelona stars Neymar, Dani Alves, and Adriano celebrated their valuable win over Celta Vigo in La Liga with a matching denim fashion choice that raised eyebrows. The Brazilian trio played a key role in the hard-fought victory, which saw Barcelona return to the league's summit. Game winner Jeremy Mathieu admitted that his side had a poor performance, attributing it to the international break, but praised the defensive efforts of teammate Gerard Pique.

Chelsea manager Jose Mourinho is rumored to be planning a summer transfer move for Atletico Madrid midfielder Koke. The club's technical director, Michael Emenalo, was reportedly present at Atletico's 2-1 victory against Deportivo on Saturday to scout the 23-year-old Spanish player. According to Spanish newspaper AS, Mourinho might offer second-choice left-back Filipe Luis as part of the deal, with the Brazilian struggling to secure a starting position at Chelsea behind Cesar Azpilicueta. Koke, who has a reported release clause of £50 million, has been a key player for Atletico, especially during their run to the Champions League final last season. If the deal goes through, it would strengthen Chelsea's midfield, which has looked tired at times this season.

Tom Ballard, a skilled climber, plans to ascend K2, 20 years after his mother Alison Hargreaves died while descending from the peak. He believes it is his destiny to follow in her footsteps, as his mother was a renowned climber who had previously conquered Everest without sherpas or bottled oxygen. Ballard was just six years old when his mother died on K2, and her decision to pursue climbing while raising a family was sometimes criticized. However, Ballard has always been passionate about climbing and recently became the first to solo climb all six of the great north faces of the Alps in the winter season.

A potential oil reserve of up to 100 billion barrels, equivalent to the entire North Sea fields, has been discovered beneath an area of England called "Britain's Dallas." The reserves are located in the Weald Basin, which spans Surrey, Sussex, Hampshire, and Kent. UK Oil & Gas Investments (UKOG) claims that this discovery could meet up to a third of Britain's oil demand within 15 years, reducing reliance on oil from the Middle East and Russia. However, industry experts remain skeptical, warning that only a fraction of the oil may be accessible for extraction and that fracking might be required to retrieve significant volumes.

The British Veterinary Association (BVA) has withdrawn its support for the shooting of free-running badgers in controversial pilot culls in Somerset and Gloucestershire. The BVA concluded that the first two years of culling had not demonstrated conclusively that ‘controlled shooting’ of free-running badgers could be effective and humane. They still support badger culling to tackle tuberculosis in cattle, however. Animal welfare campaigners welcomed the news but said the BVA’s ongoing support for cage-trapping and shooting was ‘regrettable’.

Environment Secretary Liz Truss promised to roll out more culls across the country if the Tories win the election, stating that any future Conservative government would 'take the difficult decisions to deal with this disease'. She criticized Labour for pledging to give up on culling and said the Government's strategy included cattle movement controls, vaccination in 'edge' areas around disease hotspots, and culling where the disease is rife. In Gloucestershire, just 274 badgers were culled in the second year of the pilot, falling short of the minimum 615 estimated to be needed to deliver reductions in TB in livestock. The Government claimed the low numbers reflected the 'challenges of extensive unlawful protest and intimidation' by anti-cull campaigners. In Somerset, where the other pilot cull has been carried out, a sufficient number of badgers were killed this year to lead to expected reductions in TB in cattle.

Modern technology, while meant to make life easier, often creates more problems in relationships. Social media and smartphones can cause issues on dates, such as constant phone checking, photographing food, and updating relationship statuses on Facebook too soon. To avoid these pitfalls, Blu e-cigarettes suggests tips like leaving phones off the table, not taking food pictures, and not discussing Tinder. Keeping the conversation offline and using Snapchat to update friends can also help. Avoiding bragging about Tinder matches, showing off funny memes, and recording dates with Google Glass are also important.

Ahead of this weekend's Premier League action, Sportsmail provides team news, provisional squads, betting odds, and Opta stats for Tottenham Hotspur's home clash with Aston Villa. Tottenham will be without Kyle Walker and Hugo Lloris due to injury, while Jan Vertonghen is a doubt. Aston Villa's Alan Hutton, Ashley Westwood, Scott Sinclair, and Carles Gil are expected to miss out, but Aly Cissokho could return. Odds favor Tottenham to win, with Christian Benteke being a key player to watch.

A mother named Jaye Cox decided to give birth to her sick baby, Annabelle, at 20 weeks when a serious form of Spina Bifida was discovered during scans. After Annabelle's passing, her parents contacted Angel Gowns, a not-for-profit organization that turns donated wedding dresses into outfits for babies who pass away too soon. Angel Gowns created a redesigned version of Jaye's wedding dress for Annabelle to be buried in, allowing her parents and siblings to spend time with her and remember her forever.

A black police constable, PC Ronnie Lungu, has won a race discrimination case against Wiltshire Police. The employment tribunal found that the force had unlawfully discriminated against him based on his race, as they secretly downgraded his internal assessments to make him appear unworthy of promotion. The tribunal also noted derogatory comments about Lungu based on his color, which violated his dignity. When Lungu raised concerns, they were not taken seriously by his superiors. The force, which has only 16 ethnic minority officers out of a total of just over 1,000, denied the claims. Wiltshire Chief Constable Patrick Geenty said he was "concerned" by the findings and that the force would "learn lessons" from the case. They have committed to increasing diversity in the force to better reflect the communities they serve.

American YouTube user KentuckyFriedIdiot taught his newborn daughter how to suck a plastic water bottle, resulting in a viral video with over 190,000 views. The video shows him gnawing on a drinks container, then prompting his child to follow, with the infant obediently mimicking him. They bond over their simple prop, making for an adorable moment.

A collection of rare photographs taken by Hugh Owen in the 1850s captures the early days of Bristol, a city in England. The images, up for auction, showcase the waterfront, city center, St Mary Redcliffe church, and other prominent landmarks. Some of these buildings have undergone significant transformations, while others, like St John's Gate at the Church of St John the Baptist, have remained largely unchanged. The photographs offer a fascinating glimpse into Bristol's history, with some areas experiencing dramatic changes over the past 160 years, while others have retained their charm. The albumen prints, created in the 1870s from paper negatives, provide a valuable record of Bristol before the city center was heavily bombed during World War II.

Pro-Ukip businessman Harvey Boulter, who forced Liam Fox to resign as Defense Secretary in 2011, is now attempting to defeat a "golden boy" Tory candidate, Tom Tugendhat, in the upcoming election. Boulter has already donated £30,000 to the Ukip candidate challenging Fox in his Somerset seat and is spending another £30,000 to campaign against Tugendhat in Tonbridge and West Malling, Kent. The vendetta is in response to a High Court judgment that awarded Fox a six-figure sum in damages, after Boulter made libelous remarks about him on Sky TV.

Aston Villa manager Tim Sherwood replied to a letter from 6-year-old fan Charlie Pye, who had applied for the Villa hotseat after Paul Lambert's sacking. Sherwood, who beat Charlie to the job, commended the youngster's credentials and congratulated him on being appointed captain of his local team, Norton Lindsey. Charlie had requested a chocolate bar as a win bonus and various other items, including a signed claret and blue football, a WWE wrestling figure, and some sweets. In his reply, Sherwood wished Charlie and the other supporters success and advised him to keep aiming high.

Atletico Madrid defeated bottom side Cordoba 2-0 with Antoine Griezmann scoring his 15th league goal to take the team to 62 points and surpass Valencia in the race for the third automatic Champions League berth. Saul Niguez doubled Atletico's lead, and although Valencia has a game in hand, they are now two points behind their rivals. Cordoba extended their losing streak to 10 matches and is on the verge of matching the worst run in Spain's top flight. Atletico maintains pressure on Real Madrid, who have 64 points and are four points behind leaders Barcelona. Sevilla remains in the race for Champions League qualification with a 2-0 win over Athletic Bilbao.

An 18-year-old mother-of-one, Abby Swinfield, died after taking M-Cat at a house party in Tamworth. She suffered two heart attacks and multiple organ failure. Her family believes her drink was spiked and have reported the incident to the police. A 20-year-old girl has been arrested on suspicion of supplying Class B drugs, and has been released on bail. Following Abby's death, her family is calling for more awareness of the dangers of drug use, particularly among young people.

A playground in Tokyo has been found to have dangerously high levels of radiation, raising concerns for children's health. Soil under a slide at the park showed radiation readings of up to 480 microsieverts per hour, nearly half the recommended annual limit. Authorities cordoned off the park and are investigating the source of the radiation, which could be coming from something buried underneath the park. An orange barricade has been set up around the playground, and a health advice office has been established for concerned parents. The high radiation levels have renewed concerns about radiation exposure, particularly in the wake of the 2011 Fukushima nuclear disaster. Tokyo authorities are working to identify the radioactive substance and determine the cause of the elevated levels.

Amir Khan believes Kell Brook is only calling him out for a high-paying fight, and that Brook has not fought any significant opponents in his career. Khan claims that he is not avoiding the fight with Brook, but Brook needs him to make "big money." Khan has rejected the chance to fight Brook at Wembley in June due to Ramadan, and has scheduled a fight with Chris Algieri instead. However, he has since backtracked on that decision, stating that there are "some more options on the table." Amir Khan is confident that he will face Kell Brook within the next 12 months, but argues that Brook is not a well-known fighter outside of Sheffield.

A Dallas architect, Matt Mooney, has transformed 14 shipping containers into a stunningly modern 3,700-square-foot home called 'PV14'. The home boasts a 1,400 sq ft roof deck, a 40ft long swimming pool on the ground floor, and 360-degree views of White Rock Lake and downtown Dallas. The exposed ceilings and unpainted shipping container doors maintain the industrial aesthetic. Columns and spray foam insulation were used to restore structural integrity and provide insulation, respectively. The house features maple wood flooring, floor-to-ceiling windows, and deep porches for natural light and sun protection. Mooney and his wife Barbara, a retired nurse, are preparing to move into their new home after more than two years of design and construction.

Jordon Ibe is set to sign a new five-year contract with Liverpool that will keep him at the club until 2020. The 19-year-old has impressed since returning to Liverpool this season, and his contract extension comes alongside those for Jordan Henderson and Martin Skrtel, and ongoing negotiations for Jon Flanagan. Additionally, Liverpool has secured a new three-year shirt sponsorship deal with Standard Chartered worth about £30 million per year.

Comedian Rik Mayall, known for his role as Alan B'Stard in the TV series "The New Statesman," died unexpectedly last June, leaving an estate valued at £1.2 million. Mayall did not leave a valid will, which could lead to a significant inheritance tax bill for his family and complications for the division of his estate. Experts recommend that individuals have a valid will to avoid such tax pitfalls.

Mayall's children could inherit a sum that would be liable for inheritance tax, depending on the value of his chattels, or personal belongings. His wife, Barbara, would receive £250,000 and all his chattels under intestacy rules. The family could potentially avoid the tax by setting up a deed of variation to split up the estate and reduce any sum left to the children below the tax threshold.

Interestingly, Mayall's friends and colleagues, Laurence Marks and Maurice Gran, who were the writers behind "The New Statesman," had a role in David Cameron's rise to power. They lived in the Oxfordshire constituency of Witney, where Cameron would later become MP. They advised against selecting Shaun Woodward as the Conservative candidate for Witney in 1997, but their opinion was more respected when they endorsed David Cameron as the candidate in 2001. Cameron went on to become Prime Minister, and he has remained friends with Marks and Gran, appreciating their influence in his political career.

The article describes the chaotic and stressful evacuation of Indian nationals and other foreigners from Sanaa, Yemen, due to the ongoing conflict in the region. Air India has been especially active in evacuating people, with flights going to Djibouti. Over the last few days, India has evacuated around 2,500 people from Yemen. The evacuees have had to abandon their large luggage and pay for exit visas from the Houthis. Many of them, including Damodar Thakur, a professor who lived in Sanaa for 34 years, are leaving behind their lives in Yemen and are exhausted and traumatized by the constant shelling and lack of basic amenities. The evacuation requires coordination with the Saudi air force, which provides a four-hour window for Air India to fly to and from Sanaa and a specific travel route for a safe landing. The evacuees are visibly tired and stressed but find some moment of normalcy during the flight, with the Air India crew offering drinks and the passengers socializing. Upon landing in Djibouti, the evacuees will likely disperse to their home nations, leaving behind their lives in Yemen and praying for the country's future.

An Italian priest was dismissed from a religious order in Taranto after an online lover reported him for allegedly engaging in sex with prostitutes, role play, and explicit gay chats. The priest allegedly favored sexual role-play scenarios involving his lover playing the disciple Judas Iscariot, who had to atone for betraying Jesus by becoming his slave. This latest scandal follows a series of sexual controversies involving the Vatican. The diocese confirmed the priest's dismissal but claimed no other prelates were involved.

A new study in the Journal of the American Medical Association (JAMA) has found no link between the MMR vaccine and autism, even among high-risk children with siblings who have autism. The study, which analyzed data from about 95,000 young people, is the latest in a series of research over the past 15 years that have rejected any connection between the vaccine and autism. The study found no increased risk of autism among children who had received the MMR vaccine, regardless of whether their siblings had autism.

This research adds to the growing body of evidence dispelling the myth that the MMR vaccine is associated with autism. Despite this, many parents continue to believe in a connection due to misinformation circulated in the past. The study also found that children with an older sibling with autism are less likely to be vaccinated with the MMR vaccine.

In an accompanying editorial, Dr. Bryan King emphasizes that the data is clear and that there is no evidence to suggest a relationship between the MMR vaccine and the development of autism in children with or without a sibling who has autism.

A 12-year-old girl, Jalila, was kidnapped by ISIS fighters and suffered a harrowing ordeal, including being tied up, beaten, and raped by multiple fighters, according to a new report by Human Rights Watch. The report details the accounts of 20 women and girls who escaped from ISIS, showing a system of organized rape, sexual assault, sexual slavery, and forced marriage, which constitute war crimes. The study found that ISIS fighters were kidnapping women and children as young as eight, forcing them to convert to Islam, and raping them repeatedly. The girls and women were often picked for rape through a lottery system.

Police are searching for Kenneth Stancil, a 20-year-old former student of Wayne Community College in Goldsboro, North Carolina, who allegedly opened fire in the campus library on Monday morning, killing one person and injuring another. The victim is identified as Ron Lane, a long-time employee at the college's print shop. Stancil has been described as white, approximately 5'11", with a goatee and a tattoo over his left eye. Authorities have warned that he should be considered extremely dangerous. SWAT teams and police have evacuated the campus building by building, and the lockdown has since been lifted.

The new chief executive of Rotherham council may receive a salary of up to £40,000 more than the outgoing boss due to negative publicity surrounding the grooming scandal. The council is now offering up to £200,000 for the position, compared to the £160,000 earned by former chief executive Martin Kimber. The increase is intended to attract candidates despite the council's recent controversies, which include a report that 1,400 children suffered horrific sexual abuse over 16 years and the resignation of the cabinet in February after a government report labeled the council "not fit for purpose" and "in denial" about the exploitation of mainly white girls by men of Pakistani origin.

Cesc Fabregas will wear a special protective face mask for Chelsea after breaking his nose during a match against Stoke City. The mask, featuring his initial and squad number, was created by Ortholabsport in Milan, which has previously made masks for players like Fernando Torres, Petr Cech, and Demba Ba. Fabregas traveled to Milan with Chelsea medical director Paco Biosca to have the mask fitted. The Spanish midfielder may be ready to play against Queens Park Rangers on Sunday, depending on manager Jose Mourinho's decision. John Obi Mikel should also be ready to return for the Blues at Loftus Road after resuming training with the first-team squad. However, Diego Costa is expected to miss at least two weeks of action due to a hamstring problem, with a potential return against Arsenal on April 26.

Andros Townsend scored a fantastic goal for England against Italy, relishing the opportunity to silence his critics, including Paul Merson. The 23-year-old Tottenham winger has had an up-and-down season but has earned the trust of England manager Roy Hodgson. Townsend's goal helped England secure a 1-1 draw in the friendly match in Turin.

A 73-year-old man, Joseph O'Riordan, is accused of trying to murder his wife, Amanda, after discovering she was having an affair with a postman. He stabbed her eight times, resulting in life-threatening injuries. During his trial, a letter he wrote from prison to his wife was read aloud, in which he asks her to gather his belongings, including a suit, for his trial. His wife, Amanda, broke down in the witness box as she gave evidence. She described her husband as passionate and vocally volatile, but said he had never been violent towards her before. She also admitted to having an affair, saying it was the trigger for the attack, and that she had not expected to receive the letter from her husband. The trial continues.

The UK is opening its first three proton beam therapy centers, inspired by the miraculous recovery of five-year-old brain cancer patient Ashya King, who received the treatment in Prague. The centers, located in Cardiff, London, and Northumberland, will be available to NHS cancer patients and are expected to be operational by 2017, with the first in Cardiff opening next year. The announcement comes amid increasing demand for proton beam therapy in the UK, which targets cancerous cells more precisely, reducing side effects compared to conventional radiotherapy. However, only an estimated 1 in 100 people are suitable for this treatment, and long-term impacts are not yet known. The government plans to create two NHS proton beam therapy units, opening in 2018. Ashya King's parents, Brett and Naghmeh, faced a harrowing ordeal when their son was diagnosed with a brain tumor. They discovered proton beam therapy online and defied the NHS to seek treatment for Ashya in Prague. After the family's successful battle to access the therapy, the UK is now investing in proton beam centers.

Ambulance bosses in the UK are hiring paramedics from Australia, offering £4,500 'golden hello' payments and faster recruitment processes. This is due to the NHS's inability to train enough staff to meet the rising and aging population's needs. Hospital managers are also recruiting nurses from Spain and Portugal. The ambulance service is severely understaffed, with about 1,250 posts remaining unfilled, which is 10% of what is needed. Growing numbers of paramedics are quitting the NHS, due to long queues outside A&E units and an increased number of non-urgent calls. These factors, along with the demanding nature of the job, have led many paramedics to seek positions as 'advanced practitioners' in A&E, GP surgeries, and call centers for the 111 helpline. London Ambulance Service has been hit hard by this exodus, with 230 paramedics quitting last year and 340 vacant posts, accounting for 20% of the total workforce needed.

However, Australia has a surplus of paramedics, and other understaffed ambulance services in the UK are also recruiting from there and Poland. The London Ambulance Service has hired 175 paramedics from Australia and New Zealand in September and is considering another trip later this year. The recruitment drive has saved the NHS £9 million, but it costs £50,000 to train one paramedic in Britain. The trips to Australia cost the ambulance service £90,000 in flights and hotel bills, but they return with an average of 200 paramedics. These newly hired paramedics are offered a £30,200 salary including London weighting. The service sees this as a short-term solution while they train more paramedics in the UK.

Chelsea are turning to the latest fitness technology, partnering with Technogym, to maintain their Premier League title push. The Blues have a seven-point lead and a game in hand, but are leaving nothing to chance as players train hard at their Cobham facility. Technogym has equipped the training ground with state-of-the-art equipment, and Chelsea players, including Eden Hazard and Nemanja Matic, have been working out intensely. The partnership between Chelsea and Technogym is expected to help the club achieve even more in the coming years. Meanwhile, Chelsea has two players nominated for the PFA Player of the Year awards, with Hazard the hot favorite.

This article discusses the findings of two studies that reveal the surprising intelligence of young children. In the first study, 11-month-old babies were shown to have a strong understanding of physics and were able to learn from unexpected situations. They demonstrated this by reacting with surprise to magic tricks that defied the laws of physics, such as a ball appearing to pass through a solid wall, and they tried to learn more about the situation by banging the ball on the table.

The babies were also found to be more interested in playing with the ball than a brand new toy, and they learned faster when they were surprised. The study suggests that infants use their existing knowledge of the world to form predictions and that they are more likely to learn when they are surprised.

The second study found that children who could accurately depict the human form at the age of four were more likely to be brighter in their teenage years. The study, conducted by psychologists at King's College London, involved more than 15,000 four-year-olds who were asked to draw a picture of a child. Those who drew more skillfully were likely to perform better in intelligence tests a decade later.

In summary, these studies demonstrate that young children are smarter than we might have previously thought, with the ability to learn from unexpected situations and to create accurate representations of the world around them.

Manny Pacquiao chose to train in the streets of Los Angeles on Friday by running at Griffith Park, preparing for his highly-anticipated fight against Floyd Mayweather. He swapped the gym for the great outdoors, working on his fitness and stamina. The Filipino boxer was spotted with fitness enthusiasts during his run around one of North America's largest urban parks. Pacquiao was joined by his dog Pacman and showcased his skills with shadow boxing in front of interested spectators. The 36-year-old demonstrated his core strength and impressive footwork. He recently unveiled a multicolored mouth guard for his $300 million Las Vegas showdown with Mayweather. Pacquiao also took time out to work out on mats, looking extremely focused on his training. Spectators watched as a fitness coach put him through his paces at LA's Griffith Park.

Biso, a cat who had been stuck in a wall at a Cairo train station for five years, has finally been freed. The cat survived thanks to an elderly man named Uncle Abdo, who provided food and water daily. Animal rights activists became aware of Biso's situation after a photo of his tail was posted on Facebook. They successfully coordinated with authorities to rescue the cat, but it took over five hours and Biso fled before he could be caught. Uncle Abdo is still searching for the cat inside the station.

At least 35 workers were killed at a dairy factory in Yemen after Saudi Arabian warplanes targeted Houthi rebel-controlled army camps and warehouses in the Red Sea port city of Hodeida. The airstrikes, which hit the factory's warehouses, killed and injured several workers, some of whom were reportedly crushed by rubble or burned to death. The attack comes as Saudi Arabia hinted at the possibility of launching a ground invasion in Yemen to force the Iran-backed Shiite rebels to allow current president Abed Rabbo Mansour Hadi to return to the country. Since their advance began last year, the Houthis have overrun the Yemeni capital, Sanaa, and several provinces, forcing Hadi to flee abroad. With the ongoing airstrikes and rising civilian casualties, international aid groups have expressed concern over the escalating crisis in Yemen.

Hundreds of commuters in Boston faced delays on April 7 after a truck crashed on an elevated highway over subway and rail tracks. The collision involving a box truck and a car caused officials to suspend train service under the over-hanging truck, leading to long lines for replacement shuttle buses. The truck driver and car driver both sustained non-life-threatening injuries. Investigations are ongoing, and no charges have been filed yet.

Saracens director of rugby Mark McCall praised his young players after their European heartache against Clermont, and stated that he has no intention of overspending in the competitive post-World Cup transfer market. McCall commended the performance of his young English-qualified forwards, which included Mako Vunipola and Maro Itoje. However, despite speculation that the club would sign a marquee player after chairman Nigel Wray suggested scrapping the salary cap, McCall revealed that they are willing to wait for the right person and not simply sign a high-profile player for the sake of it. McCall acknowledged the young pack's potential to be the mainstay of the club for the next four to five seasons.

The decomposing bodies of four men accused of killing 148 people in a Kenyan university attack were displayed in a primary school for all to see. The bodies were driven around the town in a pickup truck, and a large crowd gathered to view them. This came as survivor Cynthia Cheroitich, 19, was rescued after spending two days hiding in a wardrobe.

The Interior Ministry announced that five suspects had been detained, including three Kenyans of Somali origin and a Tanzanian, all of whom were associates of the alleged mastermind, Mohamed Mohamud, who has a £145,000 bounty on his head. The terrorist group al-Shabaab claimed responsibility for the attack and warned of more to come, stating, "Kenyan cities will run red with blood." In the wake of the attack, Kenya's President Uhuru Kenyatta called on Kenyan Muslims to help prevent radicalization.

Arsenal must make a swift decision on signing Petr Cech this summer or risk losing out on the goalkeeper. Chelsea's Cech is likely to leave Stamford Bridge after losing his starting spot to Thibaut Courtois. The 32-year-old has interest from Liverpool, Paris Saint-Germain, Roma, and Inter Milan. Arsenal must act quickly to avoid competition for the goalkeeper, but face obstacles like Cech's valuation and potential reluctance from Chelsea to sell to a rival.

Frankie Dettori will focus on the British Flat season this summer as Sheik Joaan Al Thani signed up Gregory Benoist to ride Al Shaqab's horses in France. Treve will continue to be partnered by Thierry Jarnet. The recruitment of Benoist could be seen as a snub for Dettori, who was replaced by Jarnet on Treve before her Arc success. However, Herbert insisted it was no longer logistically feasible to have one jockey covering both countries due to the expansion of Sheik Joaan's operation. Dettori is happy with the decision and will still ride British horses running in France. Meanwhile, Richard Hannon's Moheet finished third in the Novae Bloodstock Craven Stakes at Newmarket, and Hughes hinted that the German or French Guineas might suit Kool Kompany best. Significant Guineas action possibly took place before racing started when Charlie Hills-trained Acomb Stakes winner Connection put in a decent gallop under William Buick. Retiring champion jump jockey AP McCoy was unplaced in his final ride at Cheltenham but will ride at Ayr for the next two days and likely not ride again until his final ride at Sandown's end-of-season meeting.

Lois Lilienstein, co-star of the Canadian preschool show "Sharon, Lois & Bram's Elephant Show," has died at the age of 78. The show, which aired on CBC in Canada and on Nickelodeon in the US during the early 1990s, was known for songs like "Skinnamarink" and "Peanut Butter." Lilienstein, who moved to Toronto with her family in 1996, left the performance trio in 2000. She passed away peacefully from a rare form of cancer, diagnosed last October. CBC Television's general manager, programming, Sally Catto, paid tribute to Lilienstein, highlighting her contributions to Canadian children's television.

French freediving champion Guillaume Néry takes a breathtaking dive into Dean's Blue Hole in the Bahamas, the world's second deepest underwater sinkhole, without using any scuba gear and merely holding his breath. Although he doesn't reach the bottom, the video is still impressive due to his long underwater duration. Free divers employ sophisticated techniques to control their breathing and push the limits of apnoea. Some can hold their breath for over 20 minutes. The video was filmed in 2010 by Guillaume's girlfriend and fellow freediver Julie Gautier, at Dean's Blue Hole in the Bahamas.

A suicide bomber on a motorbike killed at least 33 people and injured over 100 in an attack on the Kabul Bank in Jalalabad, Afghanistan. The Islamic State (ISIS) claimed responsibility for the attack, marking their first claim in Afghanistan. The bomber targeted government workers collecting their pay at the bank during rush hour. The Taliban distanced themselves from the attack, and the United Nations condemned the violence, calling it a potential war crime. ISIS has been recruiting in Afghanistan, and fears about their involvement in the region have grown this year.

Laura Wells, an Australian plus-size model and environmental scientist, has launched an eco-friendly swimwear line made entirely from 100 per cent recycled materials. The collection, designed in collaboration with US brand Swimsuits For All's trend range, SwimSexy, features ocean-inspired coral reef designs and caters to all shapes with sizes ranging from 10 to 24. The line includes one and two-piece suits with unique features like zippers, criss-cross straps, plunging V-necklines, and high-waisted bottoms. The model, who previously worked with the brand on a photoshoot, hopes to provide environmentally-friendly and fashionable swimwear for curvy girls. The collection's affordability was a challenge, as recycled fabrics tend to be expensive, but the brand managed to maintain an accessible price point.

The TrackYourDose app, developed by esooka and using a mathematical model created by scientists and meteorologists from PTB and the University of Oulu, records personal radiation exposure from various sources, including medical exams, location changes, and flights. The app, which costs £1.49 ($1.99) for iOS users, uses data from 1997 to 2006 to calculate radiation levels at different flight altitudes.

 radiation levels at different flight altitudes.

Typical radiation exposure from various sources:

* 6 µSv: Dentist's X-ray
* 10 μSv: Average daily natural radiation
* 40 μSv: Flight from New York to Los Angeles
* 100 μSv: 10-hour flight across the North Atlantic
* 2,100 μSv: Annual radiation of a typical person in Europe
* 3,000 μSv: Radiation from a mammogram
* 3,600 μSv: Average annual radiation of a US citizen
* 50,000 μSv: Maximum

Blue Bell Ice Cream announced the suspension of operations at an Oklahoma production facility connected to a foodborne illness that caused the deaths of three people. The company is conducting a thorough examination of the plant to determine the exact cause of contamination. Ten recalled products were from a production line at a plant in Brenham, Texas, and were shipped to institutions in 23 states. The CDC has identified six patients with listeriosis that is indistinguishable from the one found in the contaminated ice cream product, with four of them being hospitalized in Texas. The investigation to determine if these illnesses are related to Blue Bell products is ongoing. The company's other plants continue to operate, and the Broken Arrow plant will resume operations once the investigation and necessary improvements are complete.

Jon Hamm, the star of AMC's hit show Mad Men, was reportedly involved in a college hazing incident at the University of Texas at Austin in 1990. According to court documents, Hamm and other Sigma Nu fraternity members allegedly set fire to a pledge's pants, beat him with a paddle, and used a claw hammer to drag him by his genitals during a hazing ritual. The alleged victim's mother reported the incident to the police, and Hamm was eventually charged with assault. However, the charges were dismissed in 1995 after Hamm reached a plea deal. Since then, Hamm has had a successful acting career, but has admitted that playing the complex character of Don Draper has taken its toll on him.

The ongoing dispute between the UK and Argentina over the Falkland Islands has escalated due to recent oil exploration activities and diplomatic tensions. Philip Hammond, the UK Chancellor of the Exchequer, has pledged to protect the Falklands from "Argentinian bullying" and accused Buenos Aires of provocation. This comes after Argentina summoned the British ambassador to Buenos Aires, John Freeman, to discuss recent spying revelations by Edward Snowden. The Argentine government has also threatened to take legal action against British and US oil companies exploring for fossil fuels in the area it claims as its own. The Falklands, a British overseas territory, has been under British control since 1833, but Argentina maintains its claim over the islands it calls the Malvinas.

Passengers on a Delta Air Lines flight from Tampa to New York City experienced an unexpected landing when the plane was met by firefighters in full protective suits due to a reported smoky odor. As a precaution, the flight crew shut down both engines and contacted the airport fire department. After the plane was towed to the gate, passengers deplaned normally, and the aircraft was taken out of service for inspection.

David Luiz, the injured Paris Saint-Germain defender, has taken the phrase "twiddling my hair" literally, as seen in his latest Instagram post. He sports a new hairdo in the style of a man bun. Luiz tore his hamstring during a match against Marseille and will be out for at least four weeks, potentially missing eight league matches and both legs of their quarter-final tie against Barcelona in the Champions League.

US President Barack Obama has emphasized the importance of diplomacy in addressing Iran's nuclear program, stating that it is the best option for the United States. This comes after the framework agreement reached between Iran and six world powers, which would curb Iran's nuclear capabilities in exchange for lifting economic sanctions. Obama expects a robust debate in the US and will keep Congress informed about the deal's details. Critics, including Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu and Republican opponents, argue that the deal could threaten Israel's security and allow Iran to cheat. However, Obama believes the deal is based on rigorous inspections and not trust. Final negotiations for the deal are set to take place by June 30.

A 12-year-old girl battling Leukemia for two years was kicked out of St. Joseph's Middle School, a private Catholic School in Battle Creek, Michigan, for her lack of attendance. The school sent a letter dismissing her for poor attendance and academic performance. Rose McGrath and her family are heartbroken, as she has been attending Battle Creek Catholic Schools her whole life and felt normal at school. Rose was diagnosed with leukemia in 2012 and has struggled to attend classes and complete schoolwork due to her illness. The school claimed to have made many accommodations for her, but none seem to have helped enough.

Rose's mother, Barbara McGrath, believes the school failed to provide sufficient accommodations for her daughter's serious diagnosis. The family filed a complaint with the Office of Civil Rights and is waiting for a response. Rose has been raising money for St. Baldrick's to find a cure for childhood cancer and has support from friends and family, but she now needs to figure out where she will attend school if she is not allowed back at St. Joseph's.

Passive smoking has been shown to increase cancer risk in humans, and now researchers have discovered that it also affects plants. Plants can take up nicotine from contaminated soil and plumes of smoke, which may explain high nicotine levels in some spices, herbal teas, and medicinal plants. Nicotine was previously used as an insecticide, but it is now banned in the EU due to its toxicity. Surprisingly, many food crops and plant-derived products still contain high levels of nicotine.

Researchers set out to determine if there are reasons for this beyond the use of illegal insecticides. They used peppermint plants in a series of mulching and fumigation experiments and found that nicotine levels in the plants were significantly increased after fumigation with cigarette smoke. The study shows that peppermint plants can absorb nicotine from contaminated soils and smoke, suggesting that the widespread presence of nicotine in plants may be due to sources other than illegal insecticides.

This research has implications for the food industry and sheds light on the horizontal transfer of natural products, which may explain the success of farming practices such as crop rotation and co-cultivation of certain vegetables.

Two male chameleons fought each other for a female mate in a brutal battle captured on camera near the Amber Mountain National Park in Madagascar. The aggressive chameleon won the fight, biting his rival and forcing him to retreat. The video, shot by a French-speaking video maker, shows the chameleons sizing each other up and snapping at each other before the aggressor gains the upper hand. The defeated chameleon struggles to escape, crawling across a concrete wall, while the other chameleon slowly gives chase. The video ends with both chameleons climbing onto a tree branch and disappearing from view amid leaves.

Scotland youth international Jack Cosgrove has agreed to join Edinburgh next season on a two-year deal. The 20-year-old Worcester Warriors prop, capped nine times for the Dark Blues Under 20s side, is looking forward to joining the Murrayfield outfit, which he believes has a strong set-piece game and quality players. He admires Alasdair Dickinson, an exceptional player in the same position, and is eager to learn from him. Edinburgh's recent success, including reaching the European Cup final, played a role in Cosgrove's decision.

Aaron Hernandez, a former NFL player who was convicted of murder and sentenced to life in prison without parole, is no longer known as player number 81. He has been assigned the prison number W106228 and is being held at Cedar Junction state prison in Massachusetts. Hernandez is being moved to the maximum security Souza-Baranowski Correctional Center today. He is on suicide watch and is equipped with green prison scrubs, with his tattoos being examined for gang affiliations.

According to sources, Hernandez was hooked on "angel dust" (PCP) for at least a year before the murder of Odin Lloyd. He smoked the hallucinogenic drug in marijuana cigarettes, also known as "killer joints." Friends and acquaintances reported that Hernandez became increasingly aggressive and unpleasant due to his drug use.

Before his arrest, Hernandez lived a privileged life, with a $1.3 million mansion and a celebrity status that allowed him to rub shoulders with other high-profile individuals. However, his heavy drinking, marijuana use, and association with questionable people tarnished his reputation.

Experts say that angel dust is a highly addictive substance with dangerous side effects, including hallucinations,

Manchester City manager Manuel Pellegrini has revealed that his club's young Academy players are not yet ready to step into the first-team squad, which may lead to players like Jason Denayer being recalled from loan deals. Celtic is keen on retaining the services of the 19-year-old Belgian defender Denayer, who has impressed during his loan spell at Parkhead. However, Pellegrini's confirmation that City will be investing in homegrown talent makes it an uphill battle for Celtic to keep Denayer. Current Premier League regulations require clubs to carry a minimum of eight homegrown players, which includes youngsters who have spent three of their formative years at an English club, making Denayer attractive to City. Pellegrini emphasized the need for patience in developing young players but hinted that some talented young players may break into the first team sooner.Denayer would fit the bill, and City may bring back young professionals on loan, such as Karim Rekik and Marcos Lopes, to fill gaps in the squad next season.

Ander Herrera, a Manchester United midfielder, revealed in a Q&A video that he wears both his forename and surname on the back of his shirt for superstitious reasons, following his successful spell at Athletic Bilbao. He believes that using his full name has been a source of his good fortune in the past, and he wants to continue that momentum. Herrera joined Manchester United for £29million after reaching Copa del Rey and the Europa League finals in his debut season at Bilbao in 2011-12. Recently, Herrera has become a key player for the team, contributing to their upturn in results with his impressive displays. He hopes to show more emotion as the team continues to aim for silverware in the future.

Despite a disappointing 6-1 defeat at the hands of Bayern Munich in the Champions League quarter-finals, Porto fans gave their team a hero's welcome upon their return to Portugal. The fans were proud of their team's performance in the tournament, and the players, including star striker Jackson Martinez, looked perplexed by the warm reception. Porto manager Julen Lopetegui admitted that Bayern was the better team and that his side failed to prevent their attacks, but they could still be proud of their Champions League run.

The BBC has been criticized for creating a computer game called "Syrian Journey" that simulates the ordeal of Syrian refugees fleeing their war-torn country. Players choose a character and navigate through scenarios like escaping via Turkey or Egypt, with grim outcomes such as separation from family, women being sold to militia groups, and refugees being beaten and thrown into the Mediterranean. Middle East expert Chris Walker called the game "insensitive," and Twitter users expressed outrage. Critics argue that the game, which cost around £20,000 to make, trivializes the suffering of millions of refugees. However, the BBC defends the game, stating that it has received over a million online hits a week and helps audiences understand the difficult choices faced by Syrian families.

Boston Marathon bomber Dzhokhar Tsarnaev has received another plea for mercy from his victims, Jessica Kensky and Patrick Downes, who lost limbs in the 2013 attack. The couple has joined the family of Martin Richard, an eight-year-old boy killed in the blast, in opposing the death penalty for Tsarnaev. Instead, they advocate for a life sentence without parole. In an emotional statement, Kensky and Downes expressed their desire for Tsarnaev to "disappear from our collective consciousness as soon as possible," and called their position "intensely emotional and profoundly practical." The couple's appeal comes after Tsarnaev was found guilty on all 30 counts related to the attack. A jury will now decide whether to sentence him to death or life in prison without parole.

Hamdi Ulukaya, the founder and CEO of Chobani, reached a settlement with his ex-wife, Dr. Ayse Giray, who had claimed half of the $2 billion Greek yogurt empire. The settlement, which occurred before Justice Saliann Scarpulla could rule on whether Giray could be retroactively named a shareholder in Chobani's predecessor company, ended a lawsuit that had been ongoing since 2012. Though Ulukaya's company was not an issue in their divorce, Giray based her claim on handwritten notes that she believed confirmed financial support. To avoid potentially losing $1 billion in assets, Ulukaya's camp settled the lawsuit. However, Chobani still faces challenges, as the company has been considering replacing Ulukaya as CEO due to a 2013 product recall that led to negative EBITDA and other issues.

Diego Costa is aiming to make his comeback from a hamstring injury in Chelsea's crucial clash against Arsenal on April 26. The Spain international limped off after 11 minutes in his recent return from injury during Chelsea's 2-1 win over Stoke City. He is expected to miss games against Queens Park Rangers and Manchester United but is targeting a return for the Arsenal match, which could prove pivotal in the title race. Chelsea may consider giving Costa an extended break if the title is virtually sewn up by then, but he is unlikely to require surgery. Jose Mourinho will not take any unnecessary risks with his star striker and may decide against fielding Costa against Arsenal if the title is already secured. Loic Remy is likely to start in Costa's absence against QPR on Sunday.

The England C team, which has been in existence since 1979, is facing the possibility of being axed by FA chairman Greg Dyke as part of his spending review. The team, which is managed by Paul Fairclough and consists of non-league players under 23, could be scrapped to free up funds for grassroots football projects, such as building more 3G pitches in urban coaching hubs. England C has played friendly matches against various countries, but their future is uncertain after a meeting last week. Notable players who have participated in the England C team include George Boyd, Craig Mackail-Smith, and Steve Morison, who have gone on to play for other national teams.

James Haskell, an English rugby player, showed off his inner Iron Man in a serious-looking Instagram post, joining the hype around the highly-anticipated Avengers: Age of Ultron movie. Haskell, who plays for London Wasps, posted the photo dressed as Iron Man's character, portrayed by Robert Downey Jr., on Thursday. Since returning to Wasps in 2012, Haskell has become a key part of the England squad with 57 caps to-date. He has played his rugby in various countries, including France, Japan, and New Zealand, before returning to England.

Police are urging witnesses to come forward after a middle-aged woman launched a racially-charged tirade against a Muslim woman on a Sydney train. Stacey Eden, 23, stood up for the Muslim woman and her partner, recording the incident and confronting the ranter. In the video, Eden defends the Muslim couple, saying, "She wears it (her hijab) for herself, OK!" and "It doesn't matter what they're doing... Have some respect." The Muslim couple thanked Eden for her support. Police spokeswoman contacted Daily Mail Australia to encourage witnesses to come forward. The Islamophobia Register Australia group praised Eden's actions and expressed disappointment in the ranter's remarks.

The mother of Odin Lloyd, Ursula Ward, is moving forward with a civil lawsuit against Aaron Hernandez, the man convicted of murdering her son. Ward's lawyer, Doug Sheff, stated that she wants to look Hernandez in the eye when he testifies during the wrongful death suit. Hernandez, who was convicted of first-degree murder on April 15, 2015, had a $40 million contract with the New England Patriots and did not testify during his criminal trial.

The civil suit seeks unspecified damages, and Sheff said that he plans to file papers in the next few weeks to resume the lawsuit so he can discover Hernandez's assets. The Patriots have already been dismissed from the suit, but the team has agreed to grant any money released to Hernandez to the Lloyd family.

Britain has discovered oil in the Falkland Islands, a move that could escalate tensions with Argentina, which also lays claim to the territory. The discovery, announced by British firms Premier Oil, Rockhopper Exploration, and Falkland Oil & Gas, could be worth billions of pounds. Argentine officials have threatened to prosecute oil companies operating in the area, saying they are acting illegally in Argentine territory. The discovery comes just days after Defence Secretary Michael Fallon warned of a "very live threat" from Argentina, and exactly 33 years after Argentina invaded the islands. The find is expected to lead to increased claims by Argentina over the territory, and could heighten tensions between the two countries.

A CCTV video captures the brutal attack of a three-legged cat named Freeman by two large dogs in Tarring, West Sussex. The disabled cat was sitting in its front garden when the dogs pounced, dragging it onto a neighbor's lawn. A woman in a blue car arrives, seemingly calls the dogs over, and leaves without checking on the cat, which later dies from its injuries. Police are investigating the incident and are searching for the woman and the two dogs, believed to be Dobermans. The cat's owner, Tracy Lynch, is devastated by the loss, as is her youngest son. Neighbors are also upset by the attack and the lack of concern shown by the dogs' owner.

A Chinese woman named Zhu Diandian has become an internet sensation after sharing her close relationship with her pet pig, Five Flowers. She raises Five Flowers since it was a piglet and now the pig has grown to 187lbs (13st). Despite the size, their bond remains strong as they sleep together every day. Zhu Diandian's husband is tolerant of the pig, but their pet dog is not, peering at the pig through a baby gate.

Zhu Diandian nicknamed her pet Zhu Diandian or "crazy pig" in English. She takes Five Flowers and her rabbit out for a walk, dressing the pig in a green T-shirt and body harness. She even prepares a trail of green vegetables to lead the pig to the bath for cleaning.

The Communications graduate works at a publishing company in Beijing and has almost 40,000 followers on Weibo. Her latest photos of Five Flowers in bed have received 13,000 retweets and almost 9,000 comments, mostly supportive of her unusual pet. Many commenters find the bond adorable, though some may give up eating pork after seeing the close relationship.
